        <p>Anuradhapura is one of the ancient world's great cities — a vast archaeological landscape covering 40 square kilometres of temples, palaces, monasteries, reservoirs and dagobas that served as Sri Lanka's capital for over a thousand years. Founded in the 4th century BC, it grew into one of the most sophisticated urban centres of the ancient world, with a hydraulic engineering system that made the dry northern plains bloom. Today it is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and the holiest city in Theravada Buddhism — a living religious centre where white-robed pilgrims bathe the Sacred Bo Tree in flower petals every single day.</p>

        <h2>What to See in Anuradhapura</h2>

        <h3>Sri Maha Bodhi — The Sacred Bo Tree</h3>
        <p>The most sacred site in Anuradhapura — and arguably all of Sri Lanka — is a fig tree. The Sri Maha Bodhi is said to be a sapling grown from the very tree under which the Buddha attained enlightenment in Bodh Gaya, India, brought to Sri Lanka by the princess Sanghamitta in 288 BC. It is the oldest historically documented tree in the world. Pilgrims come from across Sri Lanka and the Buddhist world to pray here — the atmosphere, particularly at dawn and dusk, is extraordinarily moving.</p>

        <h3>Ruwanwelisaya Dagoba</h3>
        <p>The great white dagoba of Ruwanwelisaya is Anuradhapura's most iconic structure — a 103-metre-tall bubble of whitewashed brick visible from miles across the plain. Built by King Dutugamunu in the 2nd century BC, it is one of the largest ancient structures in the world. The perimeter wall is decorated with a frieze of 344 elephants, symbolically supporting the relic chamber. Circumambulating the dagoba at sunset, as pilgrims do, is a profoundly memorable experience.</p>

        <h3>Jetavanaramaya</h3>
        <p>At its completion in the 3rd century AD, the Jetavanaramaya was the third tallest structure on Earth — only the two great Egyptian pyramids were higher. Today it stands at around 70 metres (having lost its upper portion), but the sheer mass of its ancient brick is still staggering. The Jetavana Museum nearby displays extraordinary relics excavated from the site.</p>

        <h3>Thuparamaya & Twin Ponds</h3>
        <p>Thuparamaya is Sri Lanka's oldest stupa, built by King Devanampiya Tissa to enshrine the Buddha's collarbone relic in the 3rd century BC. The nearby Twin Ponds (Kuttam Pokuna) are perfectly engineered ancient bathing pools for the monks of the Abhayagiri monastery — the precision of their stonework is remarkable.</p>

        <h3>Mihintale</h3>
        <p>Fifteen kilometres east of Anuradhapura, Mihintale is where Buddhism arrived in Sri Lanka. A monk named Mahinda — traditionally held to be the son of Emperor Ashoka — encountered the king Devanampiya Tissa on this rocky hilltop and converted him to Buddhism in 247 BC. The climb up 1,840 ancient stone steps to the summit dagoba is pilgrimage in miniature — and the views across the plains are spectacular.</p>

